            <p style="color: black;">
              <i>“In philosophical terms, all signals have the same flat ontological importance; what’s important is not
                what
                they are, but what an operator can do with them.”</i> - Graham Wakefield. “Generating Sound & Organizing
              Time:
              Thinking with gen~ Book 1”
              <br>
              <br>
              The same can be said about data. All data has the same flat ontological importance. What’s important is
              what can
              be done with it. I am in search of tools that can sense the digital world, interpret it, and tune it - the
              sickle and hammer of the technological age. Tools that are held by us - not subject to service or
              subscription.
              Simple tools.
              <br>
              <br>
              In the pluralistic context of India, Pakistan, Bangladesh, Taiwan, Japan, Iran - where we live in
              parallel, we
              live multiple lives, in a collective chaos - where the experience is created and consumed at scale and
              complexity - how can we think of society, community, collectivity, government, democracy, and technology?
              Who
              are we as data? And who do we want to be? What agency can we have with our mediatic selves? The power of
              creating experiences and experiencing experiences is not where the buck stops. <b>How does one get power
                to affect
                reality?</b>
              <br>
              <br>
              Authoritarianism emerged from a certain form of social media in the West and India. A different kind of
              participatory democratic model has emerged in Taiwan, and the firewall of China has produced a digital
              border
              concurrent with political borders, within which it has produced its internal logic of self and the
              digital.
              <br>
              <br>
              I propose a collaboration with Akshay Madan, a technologist and an astute observer of the political and
              media
              landscape of India. With Madan, I would like to build on the tool <a
                href="https://article-14.com/"><strong>'Grid'</strong></a>
              (Password : password) to produce an immersive environment (sound, live video
              and data analysis) analysing data and information from Live TV News.
              In its current beta form, Grid detects misinformation and manipulation in news/journalistic text. Grid
              finds
              the heroes and villains in the narrative, revealing propaganda and its tactics. It does so using
              journalistic
              frameworks (please see whitepaper in the drive link above).
              <br>
              <br>
              Using the craft of signal processing (which has been the basis for my sound work over the last decade) and
              Akshay’s knowledge of media, AI, and digital tools, a Live TV News signal is transcribed and fed into
              Grid.
              Grid gives out a minute by minute analysis - which can be plotted in various forms. This is where the
              signal
              processing happens - we encode different parameters to sounds, produce the different markers - to be
              discovered and invented during the residency. Simultaneously, the same news is fed into sentiment analysis
              AI
              models, giving us more granular control over the subjectivities of the narrative.
              <br>
              <br>
              The original purpose of the news is to reach a certain people. We analyse its geographical and linguistic
              spread map and produce a new signal/news which contains differently paced information that reveals the
              real
              structures of power and capital.
              <br>
              <br>
              Khoj would become the ‘live control room’ - where a signal is observed, processed, and a new signal
              produced
              and perhaps even distributed.
